{{Lead too short|date=June 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Rudolph Schildkraut | image = Rudolph Schildkraut.jpg | caption = Rudolph Schildkraut in 1901 | birth_date = {{birth date|1862|04|27|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Constantinople]], [[Ottoman Empire]] {{small|(now [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]])}} | death_date = {{death date and age|1930|07|15|1862|04|27|df=y}} | death_place = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S. | burial_place = [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]] | occupation = [[Actor]] | yearsactive = 1885–1930 (his death) | spouse = | parents = | children = [[Joseph Schildkraut]] }}
''' Rudolph Schildkraut '''(27 April 1862 – 15 July 1930) was an Austrian [[actor|film]] and [[theatre actor]].
== Life and career == Schildkraut was born in [[Constantinople]], in the [[Ottoman Empire]], to a [[Judaism|Jewish]] family. His parents ran a [[hotel]].<ref>Berkowitz, Joel (2005). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=aVScEpo6CS4C&pg=PA184 Shakespeare on the American Yiddish Stage]''. Iowa City: University of Iowa Press. {{ISBN|0877458006}}. p.&nbsp;184.</ref> He grew up in [[Brăila]], [[Romania]]. In [[Vienna]], he received acting lessons from Friedrich Mitterwurzer. He debuted in the early 1880s in [[Sopron]]; his first solid role came in 1885 in [[Krems an der Donau|Krems]].
In 1893 he moved to [[Vienna]] to an engagement at the newly opened [[Raimund Theater]]. In 1898 he moved to the Carl Theatre. Among other things, he played the character Wurm in'' [[Love and Intrigue]]''. In 1900 he came to the German Theatre in [[Hamburg]], 1905 to the German Theatre in [[Berlin]]. There he became one of the most important actors in the theatre company of [[Max Reinhardt]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Performance to Touch the Heart|last=Edmonds|first=Richard|date=September 22, 2000|work=[[Birmingham Post]]|page=16|quote=Shylock was played by Rudolph Schildkraut, and his portrait in the famous Max Reinhardt production hung in the Deutsches Theater in Berlin until Goebbels personally had it burned. }}</ref> His [[Shylock]], which he played in 1905 and 1913, in Reinhardt's productions of'' [[The Merchant of Venice]]'', was praised by [[Fritz Kortner]] as a "monument to the art of acting." Other major roles were the title role in ''[[King Lear]]'' (1908), [[Mephistopheles|Mephisto]] in ''[[Faust I]]'' (1909), Muley Hassan in [[Friedrich Schiller|Friedrich Schiller's]] ''[[Fiesco (play)|Fiesco]]'' (1909), the [[grave-digger]] in'' [[Hamlet]]'' (1909), and Peter Bast in [[Knut Hamsun]]'s'' From the Devil Fetched'' (1914). Schildkraut performed for the first time in the United States in 1910-11.
Schildkraut was known as a film actor in the [[German Empire]] in the early silent era. He starred in several [[Drama film|film dramas]]. His last European-made film was a biography of the German [[Zionism]] founder [[Theodor Herzl]], in which he played Herb Schildt "The Struggling Israel." In 1920 he moved permanently to the United States and made his debut the same year in [[New York City|New York]] in the play ''Silent Forces''. From 1922 he also played in the English language. In 1925 he founded his own Jewish theatre in [[the Bronx]].<ref name="Forward">{{cite news|title=Joseph Green: 'I Knew Exactly What I Wanted'|last=Edelman|first=Rob|date=January 10, 2003|work=[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]|quote=First, I became an actor with Rudolph Schildkraut's acting company in the Bronx. He and his son Joseph were soon engaged in Hollywood to play in [Cecil B.] DeMille's "King of Kings."|page=11}}</ref>
In his last five years he appeared in several Hollywood productions. His most notable film, which raised his profile in America, was ''[[The King of Kings (1927 film)|The King of Kings]]'' by [[Cecil B. DeMille]] (1927), in which he played the High Priest [[Caiaphas]].
He was married to Erna (Weinstein), with whom he had a son, [[Joseph Schildkraut]] (1896–1964), who was also known as an actor.<ref name="Forward"/>
Schildkraut died at the age of 67 years of a [[heart attack]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/1930/07/16/archive/rudolph-schildkraut-noted-jewish-actor-dies-at-70|title=Rudolph Schildkraut, Noted Jewish Actor, Dies at 70|website=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-23}}</ref> while working a film studio, in [[Los Angeles]]. He is interred in the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]] in [[Hollywood]], California. His son also died at the same age, also of a heart attack.
